n: from a vernacular short form of the Latin personal name <i>Benedictus</i> (see   Bennett  )."]},{"name":"Benedict","meanings":["English, German, and Dutch: from the personal name <i>Benedict</i>, from Latin <i>Benedictus</i> ‘blessed’. This owed its popularity in the Middle Ages chiefly to Saint Benedict of Norcia (<i>c.</i> 480–550), who founded the Benedictine order of monks at Monte Cassino and wrote a monastic rule that formed a model for all subsequent rules. No doubt the meaning of the Latin word also contributed to its popularity as a personal name, especially in Romance countries. Occasionally the English surname may derive from Latin <i>benedicite</i> ‘bless (you)’, perhaps given as a nickname to an habitual user of the expression. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed the German variant <b>Benedikt</b> and many cognates from other languages, e.g. Hungarian   Benedek  , Slovenian <b>Benedik</b> (see   Benedick  ), and also their patronymics and other derivatives, e.g. Italian   Benedetti  ."]},{"name":"Bennette","meanings":["English (Cornwall): altered form of   Bennett  ."]},{"name":"Benett","meanings":["English: variant of   Bennett  ."]},{"name":"Bennight","meanings":["Probably an altered form of English   Bennett  ."]},{"name":"Bennison","meanings":["English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name <i>Bene(i)t</i> + <i>-son</i>. See   Bennett   and compare   Benson  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Bennett was born in Durham, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son with Mary Fryth."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1450–1485":"1450–1485","1470–1537":"1470–1537","–Male":"Surnud","1485":"1485","1450":"1450","1470":"1470","1537":"1537","Durham, England":"Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Rushall, Norfolk, England":"Rushall, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","1450–1485":"1450–1485","1470–1537":"1470–1537","–Male":"Kuollut","1485":"1485","1450":"1450","1470":"1470","1537":"1537","Durham, England":"Durham, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Rushall, Norfolk, England":"Rushall, Norfolk, England"},"fr":{"–":"Décédé","1450–1485":"1450–1485","1470–1537":"1470–1537","–Male":"Décédé","1485":"1485","1450":"1450","1470":"1470","1537":"1537","Durham, England":"Durham, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Rushall, Norfolk, England":"Rushall, Norfolk, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"William Bennett est né à Durham, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Mary Fryth."},"de":{"–":"Verstorben","1450–1485":"1450–1485","1470–1537":"1470–1537","–Male":"Verstorben","1485":"1485","1450":"1450","1470":"1470","1537":"1537","Durham, England":"Durham, England, United Kingdom","Rushall, Norfolk, England":"Rushall, Norfolk, England","lifeSummary":"William Bennett wurde in Durham, England, United Kingdom geboren. Er hatte mit Mary Fryth mindestens 1 Sohn."},"ht":{"–":"Desede","1450–1485":"1450–1485","1470–1537":"1470–1537","–Male":"Desede","1485":"1485","1450":"1450","1470":"1470","1537":"1537","Durham, England":"Durham, Angletè, United Kingdom","Rushall, Norfolk, England":"Rushall, Norfolk, England"},"hu":{"–":"elhunyt","1450–1485":"1450–1485","1470–1537":"1470–1537","–Male":"elhunyt","1485":"1485","1450":"1450","1470":"1470","1537":"1537","Durham, Eng